The paper introduces a new family of string processing problems and presents linear-time solutions for them. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with fundamental string properties such as square-free factors, periodic factors, and palindromic factors, which suggests that it could also belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. The paper also involves computational geometry in the sense that it deals with finding common factors between strings, which suggests that it could belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The paper also involves formal languages, as it deals with specific properties of strings, which suggests that it could belong to the Formal Languages and Automata Theory (cs.FL) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves algorithms for finding common factors between strings, which suggests that it could belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
